<Base title="Geography" description="The continent of Avilund — its three bands, its twelve states, and a map written over with the names of saints.">
  <p class="eyebrow">The Lay of the Land</p>
  <h1>Geography of Avilund</h1>
  <p class="lede">One continent, twelve states, and four hundred years of not quite forgiving one another.</p>

  <figure>
    <img src={url('images/robertson-map.webp')} alt="A hand-drawn map of the continent of Avilund" />
    <figcaption>The continent of Avilund, bounded by the Cholera Sea (south-west), the Sanguine Sea (south-east), and the northern waters beyond.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      Until 1348 there was one Empire, and the map was simple. Then the Scion signed the
      <em>Placitum a Terminus Potentia</em> and it was not an Empire any longer. What stands in its place
      is twelve states, each ruling itself, and a scatter of towns between them that pay no taxes and
      receive no protection.
    </p>
    <p>
      There has been no open war between them since. There has not been much friendship, either.
    </p>
    <p>
      The map runs in three broad bands, and the bands are not merely political. Each keeps a different
      tier of saints, a different tongue, a different century. A traveller going north from the
      olive groves below <strong>St. Mairin&rsquo;s Gate</strong> to the halls of Heirgallad crosses
      four hundred years of history in a month&rsquo;s walk.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="prose" style="margin-top:1.6rem">
    <h2>The South — the Ecclesiastic Bishoprics</h2>
    <p>
      Warm, ancient, and steeped past saving in tradition. The heartland of the old Faith and of the
      <a href={url('saints/#primi')}>Primi</a>. Here a man is not a citizen with rights; he is a subject
      who is ruled, and punishment is harsh and swift. The South never truly joined the Revolution, and
      it has never entirely conceded that the Revolution happened.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Bishopric of <a href={url('saints/dunstan/')}>St. Dunstan</a></strong> — the crusading
        bishopric, and the seat of the Crusader City of <strong>Lysander</strong>, which is ruled by its
        Council of War: five prelates of the fighting canons. The Cathedral of St. Dunstan is the only
        cathedral outside Valdenwail to have survived Brogard, and the Abbey of the Artillery gave the
        world both gunpowder and the printing press. Since the Fourth Crusade opened the road west,
        Lysander has taken in generations of Westerners; its people are the duskiest in Avilund, and —
        for a city famed for its intolerance — the most mixed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bishopric of <a href={url('saints/severinius/')}>St. Severinius</a></strong> — the
        bishopric of the Woodland King, first man to be called a king at all.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bishopric of <a href={url('saints/mairin/')}>St. Mairin</a></strong> — named for the
        nursemaid who stole away the last living son of <a href={url('saints/avitus/')}>Avitus</a>, and
        wore the blame for it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Imperial Ecclesiarchy of Valdenwail</strong> — forty miles of dead ground, two farming
        villages, and perhaps a thousand souls all told. At its heart sprawls the castle of Valdenwail,
        home of the Scion and his strange family, ringed by an ancient forest and a thorn hedge two
        hundred feet thick. Silent knights in impossibly old plate ride its borders and ask no questions.
        No Scion has shown his face in public since 750.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="prose" style="margin-top:1.6rem">
    <h2>The Centre — the Republics</h2>
    <p>
      The modern world, such as it is: printing presses, universities, banks, corporations, and a thin
      overlay of occult activity that respectable people pretend isn&rsquo;t there. The realm of the
      <a href={url('saints/#secundi')}>Secundi</a>. This is where the Revolution was won, and the Centre
      has never let the South forget it.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Republic of Waldheim</strong> — the great city at the meeting of the Wen and the Nith,
        and the safest, most civilised ground on the continent. Governed by an elected council of eleven
        who appoint a mayor. Two hundred thousand souls in the city; another forty thousand around it.
        Its nobles must travel abroad to find anything worth hunting.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Republic of Dunstanmoore</strong> — sober, industrious, and named for the same saint the
        South made a crusader of. Where the Bishopric took Dunstan the warrior, Dunstanmoore took Dunstan
        the engineer, and neither much cares for the other&rsquo;s reading of him.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Republic of Isenveld</strong> — the most idealistic of the three, and the closest thing
        in Avilund to a government that genuinely answers to the governed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Freehold of Havilah</strong> — the Great Northern City, on the mouth of the Wen, hard
        against the Kellish and Feral marches. A chartered colony of Dunstanmoore whose charter lost its
        guarantor when the Empire fell, and which the merchant guilds have run ever since. A Chancellor
        is elected; the guilds decide the election, and prefer murder to subtlety. Paper money was
        invented here in 1388, and shares in mines and forests were being bought here by 1530. Its one
        thriving church belongs to <a href={url('saints/ulric/')}>St. Ulric</a>, patron of glory —
        and now of the merchant-houses. Dunstanmoore has never formally surrendered its claim. If the
        four-hundred-year peace breaks, it breaks here.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bishopric of <a href={url('saints/ignatius/')}>St. Ignatius</a></strong> — a bishopric in
        name, and something else in practice. Its government is unlike any other in Avilund and is
        understood by almost no one outside it. Alone among the ecclesiastic states it refuses to
        acknowledge the Scion as a secular power — a debt it has been collecting since it bought the
        Revolution&rsquo;s victory with the corpse of its own saint. It keeps the continent&rsquo;s books,
        and its Order of the Candle keeps a quieter ledger: the possessions and the hauntings, which have
        been rising since 1348.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="prose" style="margin-top:1.6rem">
    <h2>The North — the Feudal Kingdoms</h2>
    <p>
      Rough country under the Imperial Rooftop, where the <a href={url('saints/#coaevi')}>Coaevi</a> are
      honoured and the people are harder to govern. When the Imperial soldiers went home in 1348, the
      fighting nobility became warlords, the Ferals and the Kells began raiding again, and a system a
      thousand years dead came roaring back. Feudalism here is not a survival. It is a revival, and it is
      still growing.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Patrilund</strong> — the nearest of the northern kingdoms, and the first taste of the
      North for anyone coming up out of the republics.</li>
      <li><strong>Kingdom of Mantlethorn</strong> — which, with Heirgallad, was instrumental in bringing
      down the rule of the Scion.</li>
      <li><strong>Kingdom of Heirgallad</strong> — the Kellish frontier, where land disputes have been
      settled by champions since King Garamond learned the custom in 105 BC. Crowns here pass by
      intermarriage, deceit and murder.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="prose" style="margin-top:1.6rem">
    <h2>The Bones of the Land</h2>
    <p>
      The <strong>Imperial Septum</strong> is the mountain wall that divides the South from the Centre,
      and it is the reason the two have stayed different for so long. It is pierced by
      <strong>St. Mairin&rsquo;s Gate</strong>, a fortified pass on a bluff commanding the plain below —
      the <strong>Olive Plain</strong>, where in 1347 Avilundian cannon was first fired on Avilundian men.
    </p>
    <p>
      North of Waldheim rise the <strong>Peakes of <a href={url('saints/sebald/')}>St. Sebald</a></strong>.
      The <strong>Imperial Rooftop</strong> — the Peakes of St. Ulric — crowns the far North, and the
      <strong>Imperial Rampart</strong>, the Peakes of St. Abaddon, walls off the west. Beyond them lie the
      <strong>Barrier Wood</strong>, the <strong>Sea of Sorrow</strong>, and the long dry road of the
      <strong>Bellum Via</strong>, which runs two thousand miles west from Lysander into a Theatre no one
      has returned from since 1510.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose" style="margin-top:2rem">
    <h2>The Cities</h2>
    <p>
      <a href={url('geography/waldheim/')}>The City of Waldheim</a> — the great city at the meeting of
      the rivers, the old Elder city of Avitus. A gazetteer of its islands, banks, suburbs and working
      wards.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
